{{otheruses|Territorial rice fields owned by temples, shrines, or the imperial family|other uses|Oden (disambiguation)}} '''Ota''' (御田) refers to [[:en:paddy_field|territorial rice fields]] owned by [[shrines]], [[temples]], or the [[imperial family]], as well as the [[rituals]] or [[festivals]] conducted in these fields.<ref>The fields are also called "寺田" (Terada) or "神田" (Kanda), but these terms typically refer to the land itself, while the term "御田" refers specifically to the associated rituals. Additionally, the term can overlap with [[Dengaku]] practices. When read as "Oden," it generally refers to the [[Japanese cuisine]] of the same name.</ref><ref>Also called "{{ill|Terada|ja|寺田|12=draft|12=draft}}" (temple paddies), "{{ill|Kanda|ja|神田|12=draft|12=draft}}" (divine paddies), or "Goshinden." In general, "Terada" or "Kanda" refers specifically to the paddies, while "御田" often refers to events. The term is sometimes used synonymously with {{ill|Dengaku|ja|田楽|12=draft|12=draft}}, and when read as "Oden," it typically refers to the dish {{ill|Oden|ja|おでん|12=draft|12=draft}}.</ref>
As an expression of the close relationship between the [[Japanese people]] and [[rice cultivation]], many rituals associated with Ota have been passed down across [[Japan]]. Events such as the {{ill|Tahara no Ota|ja|田原の御田|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Isobe no Omita|ja|磯部の御神田|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kira River Ota Festival|ja|吉良川の御田祭|12=draft|12=draft}} have been designated as [[Important Intangible Folk Cultural Properties]]. Additional practices, such as {{ill|Otaue Matsuri|ja|御田植祭|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ta-asobi|ja|田遊び|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Rice Planting Dance|ja|田植踊|12=draft|12=draft}}, are also preserved as significant cultural heritage. In the {{ill|Imperial Palace (Japan)|ja|皇居|12=draft|12=draft}}, the [[Emperor of Japan]] personally participates in [[rice planting]] and [[harvesting]] rituals in the dedicated imperial Ota.
During the early [[Meiji period]], the [[Jōchi-rei]] (Edict of Confiscation of Temple and Shrine Lands) led to the abolition of temple and shrine territories ([[Jisha-ryō]]), temporarily resulting in the disappearance of Ota fields across Japan. However, some shrines and temples restored their Ota fields through donations from local residents. For example, the {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}} continues to maintain two Ota fields.
== Overview == '''Ota''' (御田; おた, みた, おみた, おんた, おんだ, おでん) refers to rice paddies owned by {{ill|temples|ja|寺院|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|shrines|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, or the {{ill|Imperial Household|ja|皇室|12=draft|12=draft}}, as well as events held in connection with these paddies<ref>Also called "{{ill|Terada|ja|寺田|12=draft|12=draft}}" (temple paddies), "{{ill|Kanda|ja|神田|12=draft|12=draft}}" (divine paddies), or "Goshinden." In general, "Terada" or "Kanda" refers specifically to the paddies, while "御田" often refers to events. The term is sometimes used synonymously with {{ill|Dengaku|ja|田楽|12=draft|12=draft}}, and when read as "Oden," it typically refers to the dish {{ill|Oden|ja|おでん|12=draft|12=draft}}.</ref>.
As a symbol of the deep connection between {{ill|Japanese people|ja|日本人|12=draft|12=draft}} and rice cultivation, many traditions surrounding Ota events have been passed down across Japan. Events such as the {{ill|Otamatsuri|ja|田原の御田|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Isobe no Goshinden|ja|磯部の御神田|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kira River Otamatsuri|ja|吉良川の御田祭|12=draft|12=draft}} have been designated {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Properties|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|12=draft|12=draft}}. Other customs and performances, such as {{ill|Otaue-sai|ja|御田植祭|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Taasobi|ja|田遊び|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Taue Odori|ja|田植踊|12=draft|12=draft}}, have also been preserved. At the {{ill|Imperial Palace|ja|皇居|12=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Emperor of Japan|ja|天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} personally plants and harvests rice in the Ota fields.
In the early {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治|12=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Land Reclamation Ordinance|ja|上知令|12=draft|12=draft}} abolished temple and shrine-owned land ({{ill|terasharyo|ja|寺社領|12=draft|12=draft}}), temporarily eliminating Ota fields across Japan. Some temples and shrines later revived their Ota fields through donations from local residents. {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}} maintains two Ota fields today.
== Notes == <references /> == See Also == * {{ill|Shingun|ja|神郡|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Shuinchi and Kokuinchi|ja|朱印地・黒印地|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Ta-no-Kami|ja|田の神|12=draft|12=draft}}
== External Links == * [http://www.town.katsuragi.wakayama.jp/070/040/20170330113330.html Amano Ota Festival] - A ritual at the {{ill|Niutsuhime Shrine|ja|丹生都比売神社|12=draft|12=draft}} in [[Katsuragi Town]], [[Wakayama Prefecture]]. * [https://www.city.ise.mie.jp/9198.htm Ota Festival of Sarutahiko Shrine] - A ritual at the {{ill|Sarutahiko Shrine|ja|猿田彦神社|12=draft|12=draft}} in [[Ise City]], [[Mie Prefecture]]. * [http://chikuzen-sumiyoshi.or.jp/sp/event/spring.html#01 Ota Festival of Sumiyoshi Shrine] - A ritual at the {{ill|Sumiyoshi Shrine (Fukuoka)|ja|住吉神社 (福岡市)|12=draft|12=draft}} in [[Hakata Ward]], [[Fukuoka City]]. * [http://www.town.miyazaki-misato.lg.jp/2535.htm Ota Festival of Tashiro Shrine] - A ritual at Tashiro Shrine in [[Misato Town]], [[Miyazaki Prefecture]].
