{{otheruses|Territorial rice fields owned by temples, shrines, or the imperial family|other uses|Oden (disambiguation)}} '''Ota''' (御田) refers to [[:en:paddy_field|territorial rice fields]] owned by [[shrines]], [[temples]], or the [[imperial family]], as well as the [[rituals]] or [[festivals]] conducted in these fields.<ref>The fields are also called "寺田" (Terada) or "神田" (Kanda), but these terms typically refer to the land itself, while the term "御田" refers specifically to the associated rituals. Additionally, the term can overlap with [[Dengaku]] practices. When read as "Oden," it generally refers to the [[Japanese cuisine]] of the same name.</ref><ref>Also called "{{ill|Terada|ja|寺田|qq=draft|qq=draft}}" (temple paddies), "{{ill|Kanda|ja|神田|qq=draft|qq=draft}}" (divine paddies), or "Goshinden." In general, "Terada" or "Kanda" refers specifically to the paddies, while "御田" often refers to events. The term is sometimes used synonymously with {{ill|Dengaku|ja|田楽|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and when read as "Oden," it typically refers to the dish {{ill|Oden|ja|おでん|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.</ref>
As an expression of the close relationship between the [[Japanese people]] and [[rice cultivation]], many rituals associated with Ota have been passed down across [[Japan]]. Events such as the {{ill|Tahara no Ota|ja|田原の御田|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Isobe no Omita|ja|磯部の御神田|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Kira River Ota Festival|ja|吉良川の御田祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}} have been designated as [[Important Intangible Folk Cultural Properties]]. Additional practices, such as {{ill|Otaue Matsuri|ja|御田植祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ta-asobi|ja|田遊び|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Rice Planting Dance|ja|田植踊|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, are also preserved as significant cultural heritage. In the {{ill|Imperial Palace (Japan)|ja|皇居|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the [[Emperor of Japan]] personally participates in [[rice planting]] and [[harvesting]] rituals in the dedicated imperial Ota.
During the early [[Meiji period]], the [[Jōchi-rei]] (Edict of Confiscation of Temple and Shrine Lands) led to the abolition of temple and shrine territories ([[Jisha-ryō]]), temporarily resulting in the disappearance of Ota fields across Japan. However, some shrines and temples restored their Ota fields through donations from local residents. For example, the {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} continues to maintain two Ota fields.
